  "id": "",
  "summary": "Heavily obfuscated JavaScript across 45 files in hidden.ad/ directory",
  "details": "The package ships 45 heavily obfuscated JavaScript files under a hidden `.ad/` directory, including suggestively named modules (`phone-validator.js`, `sms-providers.js`, `smtp-health-cache.js`, `web-command.js`, `from-generator.js`) and a series of opaque single-letter files (`x0.js` through `xz.js`). All files use hex-identifier obfuscation (e.g., `_0x37ca78`, `_0x2abb22`) consistent with automated string/control-flow obfuscators that hide intent from reviewers. The combination of a hidden directory, abuse-themed filenames (SMS/SMTP/phone-validator naming patterns are commonly associated with bulk-messaging or credential-abuse tooling), and uniform obfuscation across the entire content set is highly atypical for a legitimate library. However, deeper tracing of import-time and lifecycle behavior did not complete, so the specific runtime effect on an installer (exfil endpoint, credential read, dropper, or simply user-invoked tooling) has not been confirmed in this analysis. Routing to human review for de-obfuscation and confirmation of whether the harmful code paths fire on install/import or only on explicit user invocation.",
